1

Make a labeled histogram (with 30 bins) of the ages of the houses in the data set, and describe the distribution.

current_year = as.numeric(format(Sys.Date(), "%Y"))

ames_train$Age = current_year - ames_train$Year.Built

ggplot(data = ames_train,aes(Age)) +
  geom_histogram( col="blue",
                 aes(fill=..count..),
                 bins=30) +
  labs(title="Histogram for House Age") +
  labs(x="Age", y="Count")

The distribution is right skewed and asymmetric. The peaks are clearly for newer houses. Also, there seem to be a few potential outliers at the very right.

We can see that there are very few older houses. As the age increases, the amount of houses goes down.

Although theres an interesting point for houses between 25 and 35 years of age. The number of houses is around the same as houses between 65 and 100 years old.

4

We want to predict the natural log of the home prices. Candidate explanatory variables are lot size in square feet (Lot.Area), slope of property (Land.Slope), original construction date (Year.Built), remodel date (Year.Remod.Add), and the number of bedrooms above grade (Bedroom.AbvGr). Pick a model selection or model averaging method covered in the Specialization, and describe how this method works. Then, use this method to find the best multiple regression model for predicting the natural log of the home prices.

price_pred_model_lot_area = lm(log(price) ~ Lot.Area + Land.Slope + Year.Built + Year.Remod.Add + Bedroom.AbvGr, data = ames_train)
                
summary(price_pred_model_lot_area)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = log(price) ~ Lot.Area + Land.Slope + Year.Built + 
##     Year.Remod.Add + Bedroom.AbvGr, data = ames_train)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -2.0878 -0.1651 -0.0211  0.1657  0.9945 
## 
## Coefficients:
##                  Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)    -1.371e+01  8.574e-01 -15.996  < 2e-16 ***
## Lot.Area        1.028e-05  1.106e-06   9.296  < 2e-16 ***
## Land.SlopeMod   1.384e-01  4.991e-02   2.773  0.00565 ** 
## Land.SlopeSev  -4.567e-01  1.514e-01  -3.016  0.00263 ** 
## Year.Built      6.049e-03  3.788e-04  15.968  < 2e-16 ***
## Year.Remod.Add  6.778e-03  5.468e-04  12.395  < 2e-16 ***
## Bedroom.AbvGr   8.686e-02  1.077e-02   8.063 2.12e-15 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 0.279 on 993 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.5625, Adjusted R-squared:  0.5598 
## F-statistic: 212.8 on 6 and 993 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16
step <- stepAIC(price_pred_model_lot_area, direction="backward", k=log(1000))
## Start:  AIC=-2511.42
## log(price) ~ Lot.Area + Land.Slope + Year.Built + Year.Remod.Add + 
##     Bedroom.AbvGr
## 
##                  Df Sum of Sq    RSS     AIC
## <none>                        77.322 -2511.4
## - Land.Slope      2    1.4281 78.750 -2506.9
## - Bedroom.AbvGr   1    5.0628 82.385 -2454.9
## - Lot.Area        1    6.7292 84.051 -2434.9
## - Year.Remod.Add  1   11.9642 89.286 -2374.5
## - Year.Built      1   19.8546 97.177 -2289.8
final_price_pred_model_lot_area = lm(log(price) ~ Lot.Area + Land.Slope + Year.Built + Year.Remod.Add + Bedroom.AbvGr, data = ames_train)

To find the best model, we used stepwise model selection by AIC. A process we could do manually, but the stepAIC function will do it for us.

The way it works is, it works backwards through the model space, removing variables until AIC can be no longer be lowered. It takes as input a full model, and a penalty parameter, which in this case we will use 1000, being the sample size.

By using this technique we found out that that all the variables selected are strong predictors for the natural log of the home prices. So the final model includes all varaibles:

1. Lot.Area 2. Land.Slope 3. Year.Built 4. Year.Remod.Add 5. Bedroom.AbvGr

7

Do you think it is better to log transform Lot.Area, in terms of assumptions for linear regression? Make graphs of the predicted values of log home price versus the true values of log home price for the regression models selected for Lot.Area and log(Lot.Area). Referencing these two plots, provide a written support that includes a quantitative justification for your answer in the first part of question 7.

price_data_set = data.frame(
   index = seq.int(nrow(ames_train)),
  logPrice = log(ames_train$price),
  priceLotArea = final_price_pred_model_lot_area$fitted.values,
  priceLogLotArea = final_price_pred_model_log_lot_area$fitted.values,
  logPMinusLotArea = log(ames_train$price) - final_price_pred_model_lot_area$fitted.values,
  logPMinusLogLotArea = log(ames_train$price) - final_price_pred_model_log_lot_area$fitted.values
)

ggplot(price_data_set, aes(index)) +
  geom_line(aes(y=logPrice), colour="red") + 
  geom_line(aes(y=priceLotArea), colour="yellow")

ggplot(price_data_set, aes(index)) +
  geom_line(aes(y=logPrice), colour="red") +
  geom_line(aes(y=priceLogLotArea), colour="blue")  

ggplot(price_data_set, aes(index)) +
  geom_line(aes(y=logPrice), colour="red") +
  geom_line(aes(y=priceLotArea), colour="yellow") + 
  geom_line(aes(y=priceLogLotArea), colour="blue") 

ggplot(price_data_set, aes(index)) +
  geom_line(aes(y=logPMinusLotArea), colour="red") +  
  geom_line(aes(y=logPMinusLogLotArea), colour="blue")

ggplot(price_data_set, aes(index)) +
  geom_line(aes(y=logPMinusLogLotArea), colour="blue") +
  geom_line(aes(y=logPMinusLotArea), colour="red")

We created a data set with 6 variables:

  1. index: a sequential index to use as reference
  2. logPrice: The actual values for log(price)
  3. priceLotArea: The predicted values for log(price) using the model that includes the Lot.Area variable.
  4. priceLogLotArea: The predicted values for log(price) using the model that includes the log(Lot.Area) variable.
  5. logPMinusLotArea: The difference between the actual log(price) values and the predicted values for log(price) using the model that includes the Lot.Area variable.
  6. logPMinusLogLotArea: The difference between the actual log(price) values and the predicted values for log(price) using the model that includes the log(Lot.Area) variable.

To visualize the differences between 3 and 4, we made 3 graphs:

First graph includes 2 and 3. Second graph includes 2 and 4. Third graph includes 2,3 and 4.

But, we couldnt really tell if theres a clear between 3 and 4. So we plotted the differences between the actual values and the predicted values. For this we did 2 graphs, which are essentially the same one, but they differ in which variable is on top:

Fourth graph includes 5 and 6, where 5 is on top. Fift graph includes 5 and 6, where 6 is on top.

By looking at the graphs, we cant really tell if 3 is better than 4, or vice versa. In some points one is better than the other, but overall, theres no clear signal that one is better than the other
